e]]''\n| Various roles\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 1993\u20131998\n| ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]''\n| Dorothy Jennings\n| 100 episodes<br>Nominated\u2014<br>[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Award<br>for Outstanding Supporting Actress<br>in a Drama Series]] (1995)\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Chicago Hope]]''\n| Beverly Kronk\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]''\n| Edna Raines\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Frasier]]''\n| Penelope Janvier\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002\n| ''[[Pasadena (TV series)|Pasadena]]''\n| Lillian Greeley\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2002\u20132004\n| ''[[Judging Amy]]''\n| Diane McCarty\n| 2 episodes\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Barbara Babcock}}\n*{{IMDb name|0044823}}\n*{{Amg name|3098}}\n\n<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n\n{{EmmyAward DramaLeadActress}}\n\n<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babcock, Barbara}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:Wellesley College alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kansas]]\n[[Category:People from Carmel-by-the-Sea, California]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Riley, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:University of Lausanne alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:Miss Porter's School alumni]]\n[[Category:People with Parkinson's disease]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American character actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|Stanford law professor|Barbara A. Babcock|}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Barbara Babcock\n| image        = Barbara Babcock.jpg\n| image_size   = 240px\n| caption      = Babcock in 1968\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1937|2|27|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Fort Riley]], [[Kansas]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1956\u20132004\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Jay Sheffield]]|1962|1968}}\n| awards       = '''[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]]'''<br>1981 ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''\n}}\n\n'''Barbara Babcock''' (born February 27, 1937) is an American [[character actor|character actress]]. She is perhaps best known for her role as Grace Gardner on ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'', for which she won an [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Lead Actress\u2014Drama Series in 1981, and her role as Dorothy Jennings on ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'', for which she was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] in 1993.\n\n==Early life==\nAlthough she was born in the United States, Babcock spent a large part of her childhood in [[Tokyo]], Japan, where her father, [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] Gen. Conrad Stanton Babcock, Jr., was stationed.<ref name=\"gt\">{{cite news|title=Barbara Babcock 'intriguing'|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4403171/the_gettysburg_times/|work=The Gettysburg Times|date=April 17, 1982|location=Gettysburg, Pennsylvania|page=16|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = February 21, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref> She learned to speak [[Japanese language|Japanese]] before English.\n\nBabcock studied at Switzerland's [[University of Lausanne]] and Italy's [[University of Milan]].<ref name=gt/> She also attended [[Miss Porter's School]] and graduated from [[Wellesley College]],<ref name=\"kt\">{{cite news|title=State Secrets|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4403381/the_kokomo_tribune/|agency=The Kokomo Tribune|date=November 13, 1987|location=Indiana, Kokomo|page=24|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = February 23, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref> where she was a classmate of [[Ali MacGraw]].\n\n==Career==\nBabcock's television appearances began in 1956. They included several episodes of the original series of ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'', although much of her work on the show consisted of uncredited voice roles. In 1968, she made her debut on the big screen in the [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] western ''[[Day of the Evil Gun]]'', followed by roles in the films ''[[Heaven with a Gun]]'', co-starring [[Glenn Ford]], ''[[Bang the Drum Slowly (film)|Bang the Drum Slowly]]'', ''[[Chosen Survivors]]'', ''[[The Black Marble]]'', ''[[Back Roads (1981 film)|Back Roads]]'', ''[[The Lords of Discipline (film)|The Lords of Discipline]]'' and ''[[That Was Then... This Is Now]]''. From 1978 to 1982, she played the role of Liz Craig on the [[CBS]] soap opera ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''. Other notable films include ''[[Heart of Dixie (film)|Heart of Dixie]]'', ''[[Happy Together (1989 American film)|Happy Together]]'', ''[[Far and Away]]'' and ''[[Space Cowboys]]''.\n\nBabcock won the 1981 Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress\u2014Drama Series for her work on ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''.<ref name=\"ea\">{{cite web|title=Awards Search: Barbara Babcock|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominations/award-search?search_api_views_fulltext=Barbara+Babcock&submit=Search&field_celebrity_details_field_display_name=&field_show_details_field_nominee_show_nr_title=&field_show_details_field_network=All&field_show_details_field_production_company=All&field_nominations_year=1949-01-01+00%3A00%3A00&field_nominations_year_1=2016-01-01+00%3A00%3A00&field_award_category=All|website=Television Academy|accessdate=23 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322204146/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominations/award-search?search_api_views_fulltext=Barbara+Babcock&submit=Search&field_celebrity_details_field_display_name=&field_show_details_field_nominee_show_nr_title=&field_show_details_field_network=All&field_show_details_field_production_company=All&field_nominations_year=1949-01-01+00:00:00&field_nominations_year_1=2016-01-01+00:00:00&field_award_category=All|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> She appeared in 16 episodes of the NBC police drama as Grace Gardner from 1981 to 1986. She starred in the short-lived TV series ''The Four Seasons'' in 1984, ''[[Mr. Sunshine (1986 TV series)|Mr. Sunshine]]'' in 1986 and ''[[The Law & Harry McGraw]]'' in 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/p3098|title=Barbara Babcock - Biography, Movie Highlights and Photos - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1993 to 1998, she played the role of Dorothy Jennings on ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'' for which she was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series in 1993. (However, the Emmy Awards website lists the nomination for 1995.)<ref name=ea/> She was voted one of the 50 Most Beautiful People in the World by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20108044,00.html|title=Barbara Babcock|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{imdb name|id=0044823|name=Barbara Babcock|section=bio}}</ref> After completion of the show in 1998, she appeared in ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]'', ''[[Chicago Hope]]'', ''[[Frasier]]'' and ''[[Judging Amy]]''. From 2001 to 2002, she played the role of the mother of [[Dana Delany]]'s character in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] drama series ''[[Pasadena (TV series)|Pasadena]]''. \n\nIn 2004, Babcock was diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]] and now resides in [[Carmel, California]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carmelmagazine.com/archive/18su/carmel-through-the-eyes-of-barbara-babcock|title=Carmel Through the Eyes of Barbara Babcock \u2013 Carmel Magazine|website=carmelmagazine.com}}</ref>.\n\nBabcock and actress Susan Bjurman received a patent for a shampoo that they developed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buck |first1=Jerry |title=There's more than Grace |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/36121890/barbara_babcock/ |accessdate=September 18, 2019 |work=Spokane Chronicle |agency=Associated Press |date=April 16, 1982 |location=Washington, Spokane |page=39|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Day of the Evil Gun]]''\n| Angie Warfield\n|\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[Heaven with a Gun]]''\n| Mrs. Andrews\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[The Last Child (film)|The Last Child]]''\n| Shelley Drumm\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Bang the Drum Slowly (film)|Bang the Drum Slowly]]''\n| Team Owner\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Chosen Survivors]]''\n| Dr. Lenore Chrisman\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Christmas Miracle in Caufield, U.S.A.]]''\n| Rachel Sullivan\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''Operating Room''\n| Jean Lawrence\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''Survival of Dana''\n| Lorna Sims\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[The Black Marble]]''\n| Madeline Whitfield\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Back Roads (1981 film)|Back Roads]]''\n| Rickey's Mom\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''Memories Never Die''\n| Louise Lowry\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1983\n| ''[[Quarterback Princess]]''\n| Judy Maida\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Lords of Discipline (film)|The Lords of Discipline]]''\n| Abigail St. Croix\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Attack on Fear]]''\n| Jane Dutton\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[That Was Then... This Is Now]]''\n| Mrs. Douglas\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''News at Eleven''\n| Joanna Steckler\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1989\n| ''[[Happy Together (1989 American film)|Happy Together]]''\n| Ruth Carpenter\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Heart of Dixie (film)|Heart of Dixie]]''\n| Coralee Claibourne\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[A Family for Joe]]''\n| Miss Quinn Collins\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Far and Away]]''\n| Nora Christie\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Fugitive Nights: Danger in the Desert''\n| Rhonda Devon\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[A Mother's Instinct]]''\n| Mrs. Mitchell\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''Childhood Sweetheart?''\n| Rose Carlson\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1999\n| ''A Vow to Cherish''\n| Ellen Brighton\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman: The Movie]]''\n| Dorothy Jennings\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Space Cowboys]]''\n| Barbara Corvin\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Home Alone 4]]''\n| Molly\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[NBC Sunday Showcase]]''\n| Annie Lee\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis]]''\n| Pamela Osborne\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[The Munsters]]''\n| Miss Guthrie\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1966\u20131967\n| ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]''\n| Elaine Carey\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[The Lucy Show]]''\n| English Teacher\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Mission: Impossible (1966 TV series)|Mission: Impossible]]''\n| Major Maria Felder\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1967\u20131968\n| ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]''\n| Mea 3/Philana/voice-over work\n| \"[[A Taste of Armageddon]]\" and<br>\"[[Plato's Stepchildren]]\",<br>plus 4 other episodes\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[Family Affair]]''\n| Pamela\n|1 episode\n|-\n| 1967\u20131970\n| ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]''\n| Mama Bear/Maria Schmidt\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Night Gallery]]''\n| Flora Alden\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]''\n| Mary Hale\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Banyon]]''\n| Caroline Wheeler\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1973\n| ''[[Shaft (TV series)|Shaft]]''\n| Jane Cunningham\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Love, American Style]]''\n| Anna Scott\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1968\u20131973\n| ''[[Mannix]]''\n| Ellen West\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[The Streets of San Francisco]]''\n| Judith 'Judy' Tyrell\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Starsky & Hutch]]''\n| Ellen Forbes\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 1977\n| ''[[McMillan & Wife]]''\n| Lydia Corman\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]''\n| Melissa Asten\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[The Rockford Files]]''\n| Karen Hall\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Logan's Run (TV series)|Logan's Run]]''\n| Marianne\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Salem's Lot (1979 miniseries)|Salem's Lot]]''\n| June Petrie\n| Television miniseries\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Benson (TV series)|Benson]]''\n| Lily Maxwell\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1981\n| ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]''\n| Karen\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Flo]]''\n| Louise Browning\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1978\u20131982\n| ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''\n| Liz Craig\n| 16 episodes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Cheers]]''\n| Lana Marshall\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''The Four Seasons''\n| Lorraine Elliot\n| 13 episodes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Hotel (U.S. TV series)|Hotel]]''\n| Monica Shawcross\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Mr. Sunshine (1986 TV series)|Mr. Sunshine]]''\n| Mrs. June Swinford\n| 11 episodes\n|-\n| 1981\u20131982, 1984, 1986\n| ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''\n| Grace Gardner\n| 16 episodes<br>[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Award<br>for Outstanding Lead Actress<br>in a Drama Series]] (1981)\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1987\n| ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents (1985 TV series)|The New Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]''\n| Cissie Enright\n| 1 episode<br>[[CableACE Award|CableACE Award for<br>Outstanding Actress in<br>a Dramatic Series]] (1988)\n|-\n| ''[[Remington Steele]]''\n| Marisa Peters\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1987\u20131988\n| ''[[The Law & Harry McGraw]]''\n| Ellie Maginnis\n| 16 episodes\n|-\n| 1989\u20131990\n| ''[[Empty Nest]]''\n| Paula Conroy\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1990\n| ''[[The Golden Girls]]''\n| Charmaine Hollingsworth\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[China Beach]]''\n| Lt. Col. Libby Heiss\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Wings (1990 TV series)|Wings]]''\n| Mae Hackett\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1985\u20131993\n| ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n| Various roles\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 1993\u20131998\n| ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]''\n| Dorothy Jennings\n| 100 episodes<br>Nominated\u2014<br>[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Award<br>for Outstanding Supporting Actress<br>in a Drama Series]] (1995)\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Chicago Hope]]''\n| Beverly Kronk\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]''\n| Edna Raines\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Frasier]]''\n| Penelope Janvier\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002\n| ''[[Pasadena (TV series)|Pasadena]]''\n| Lillian Greeley\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2002\u20132004\n| ''[[Judging Amy]]''\n| Diane McCarty\n| 2 episodes\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Barbara Babcock}}\n*{{IMDb name|0044823}}\n*{{Amg name|3098}}\n\n<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n\n{{EmmyAward DramaLeadActress}}\n\n<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babcock, Barbara}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:Wellesley College alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kansas]]\n[[Category:People from Carmel-by-the-Sea, California]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Riley, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:University of Lausanne alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:Miss Porter's School alumni]]\n[[Category:People with Parkinson's disease]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Babcock"}
