{"title_page": "Banijay Group", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2013}}\n{{COI|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Banijay Group\n| logo = \n| former_name = Banijay Entertainment {{Small|(2008-2011)}}\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Entertainment]]\n| predecessor = [[Zodiak Media]] (2007-2016)\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2008}} in [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| founder = [[St\u00e9phane Courbit]]\n| location = \n| location_city = [[Paris]]\n| location_country = [[France]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = St\u00e9phane Courbit ([[Chairman]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Our People - Banijay Group|url=http://www.banijay.com/people|website=www.banijay.com|accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref><br>Marco Bassetti ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br>Peter Langenberg ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])<br />Marie Schweitzer (EVP Strategy and Business Development)<br> Sophie Kurinckx (Group CFO)<br> Nicolas Chazarain (Group Chief Legal Officer)\n| products = \n| owners = LDH (67%)<br>[[Vivendi]] (33%)\n| num_employees = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.banijay.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Banijay Group''' is a leading independent French global production and distribution business founded in January 2008 by [[St\u00e9phane Courbit]] as '''Banijay Entertainment'''. \n\nThrough its production entities and strategic partnerships, Banijay Group brings together creative entrepreneurs. Present in 16 territories across [[Europe]] ([[France]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Belgium]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Germany]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Sweden]], [[Denmark]], [[Norway]], [[Russia]] and [[Finland]]), the [[United States]], [[Asia]] (including [[India]]), [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]], the group's key formats and productions include Versailles, The Secret Life of 4 Year Olds, Temptation Island, Survivor, Keeping up with the Kardashians, The Real World, Fort Boyard, The Restaurant, Wife Swap, and Occupied.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banijay.com/|title=Banijay Group - We are Banijay|website=www.banijay.com}}</ref>\n\nBanijay's merger with [[Zodiak Media]], completed in February 2016, made the company the largest independent content producer in the world with revenues of around $1 billion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.televisionpost.com/news/banijay-zodiak-merge-to-create-worlds-largest-independent-production-company/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221105511/http://www.televisionpost.com/news/banijay-zodiak-merge-to-create-worlds-largest-independent-production-company/ |archive-date=2017-02-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Its catalogue of more than 22,000 hours of content across all genres, 50% of which is third-party programming from independent producers and networks, is distributed globally by Banijay Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todotvnews.com/news/Zodiak-Rights-Becomes-Banijay-Rights.html|title=Zodiak Rights Becomes Banijay Rights|first=|last=@todotvnews|website=Todotvnews}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.zodiakrights.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207131212/https://www.zodiakrights.com/ |archive-date=2017-02-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2019, the company announced it has entered into a definitive agreement to acquire 100% of the equity of [[Endemol Shine Group]], with its catalogue increasing to 85,000 hours of content across all genres and nearly 200 film and TV production companies.<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-26/banijay-to-acquire-black-mirror-producer-endemol-shine-group</ref> In February 2020, Banijay raised $2,600,000,000 in refinancing for acquiring Endemol Shine.<ref>https://deadline.com/2020/02/banijay-group-refinances-endemol-shine-group-takeover-1202856196/</ref>\n\nBanijay is chaired by St\u00e9phane Courbit and led by Marco Bassetti.\n==Acquisitions==\n\nBanijay Group (initially Banijay Entertainment), is the result of successive production company acquisitions and partnerships driven by French entrepreneur and TV producer, St\u00e9phane Courbit (LOV Group).\n\nIn October 2008, Banijay acquired Air Productions, the production company of famous French host [[Nagui]]. In 2009, Banijay made three acquisitions: 51% of Spanish production company Cuarzo Producciones on 12 January,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/9984/banijay-adquiere-el-51-del-accionariado-de-cuarzo-producciones/|title=Banijay adquiere el 51% del accionariado de Cuarzo Producciones|publisher=}}</ref> 50% of German producer [[Brainpool TV]] on 2 July<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/biz/news/banijay-buys-50-stake-in-brainpool-1118005629/|title=Banijay buys 50% stake in Brainpool|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=2 July 2009|publisher=}}</ref> and the entire television division of [[Copenhagen]]-based film studio [[Nordisk Film & TV]] on 12 October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/banijay-acquires-nordisk-films-tv-89927|title=Banijay acquires Nordisk Film's TV arm|publisher=}}</ref> In March 2010, Banijay acquired American production company [[Bunim/Murray Productions]] for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bunim-murray-acquired-frances-banijay-22026|title=Bunim-Murray acquired by France's Banijay|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Banijay acquired a majority stake in Australian production company [[Screentime]], which included a New Zealand division (Screentime New Zealand) and a 49% stake in Irish producer [[Shinawil]] which was sold in 2015.<ref>http://if.com.au/2012/09/04/article/Banijay-Group-acquires-majority-stake-in-Screentime/XWNVYNIBXL.html</ref> That same year, French 24/7 celebrity news television channel Non Stop People and popular French television host [[Cyril Hanouna]]'s H2O Productions became new members of the Group,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribune.fr/technos-medias/medias/20120724trib000710651/stephane-courbit-rachete-la-societe-de-production-de-cyril-hanouna-et-boucle-le-rachat-d-everest-poker-.html|title=St\u00e9phane Courbit rach\u00e8te la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de production de Cyril Hanouna et boucle le rachat d'Everest Poker|publisher=}}</ref> followed in 2013 by Italian producer Ambra Multimedia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2013/04/marco-bassetti-named-ceo-of-banijay-group-acquires-italys-ambra-multimedia-485533/|title=Marco Bassetti Named CEO Of Banijay; Group Acquires Italy\u2019s Ambra Multimedia|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=29 April 2013|publisher=}}</ref> and Spanish independent producer, DLO Producciones.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/banijay-group-acquires-spanish-tv-625359|title=Banijay Group Acquires Spanish TV Production Firm DLO|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Banijay launched Banijay Studios North America in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/news/miptv-banijay-taps-former-endemol-exec-david-goldberg-to-launch-banijay-studios-north-america-1201153120/|title=MipTV: Banijay Taps David Goldberg to Launch Banijay Studios North America|first=Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=5 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref> On 9 January 2015, Banijay acquired Stephen David Entertainment, a [[New York City]]-based producer of television dramas and documentaries, expanding its North American presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/banijay-group-buys-controlling-share-in-stephen-david-entertainment-1201395774/|title=Banijay Group Buys Controlling Share in Stephen David Entertainment|first=Brian|last=Steinberg|date=8 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2015, Banijay Group announced that it would merge with [[Zodiak Media]], making the former the world's only largest television content production and distribution company not owned by a media conglomerate, as other large television content companies are ([[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]] is owned by [[Bertelsmann]] via [[RTL Group]], [[ITV Studios]] is owned by [[ITV plc]], [[Endemol Shine Group]] is a joint venture between [[The Walt Disney Company]] and [[Apollo Global Management]] and [[All3Media]] is a joint venture between [[John C. Malone]]-controlled companies [[Liberty Global]] and [[Discovery, Inc.]]). The merger was completed in February 2016.<ref>http://www.gruppodeagostini.it/(S(evycbiepmdyz4vyc3zd44nee))/paginaAllegati.aspx?IdAllegato=554</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/global/banijay-zodiak-to-merge-to-create-1-billion-production-house-1201549764/|title=Banijay, Zodiak to Merge to Create $1 Billion Production House|first=Leo Barraclough,Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=28 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Since then, Banijay Group continues to grow, both internally and externally.\n\nIn July 2017, Banijay Group acquired British producer Castaway Television Productions, the team behind global hit format, Survivor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/banijay-group-raises-416-million-castaway-survivor-acquisition-1202125847/|title=Banijay Raises $416M To Help Finance Acquisition Of \u2018Survivor\u2019s Castaway Prods|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=10 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In February 2018, it acquired another British producer, Wonder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/02/banijay-acquires-7wonder-production-arm.html|title=Banijay acquires Wonder production arm|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=28 February 2018|work=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, three new units, Banijay Studios Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/global/banijay-studios-italy-bows-to-produce-premium-scripted-content-1202856309/|title=Banijay Studios Italy Bows to Produce Premium Scripted Content|first=Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=25 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Banijay Asia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/banijay-rights-partners-deepak-dhar-launch-banijay-asia-1202747361/|title=Banijay Group Partners With Deepak Dhar to Launch Banijay Asia|first=Robert|last=Mitchell|date=9 April 2018|publisher=}}</ref> and Banijay Productions Germany,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/banijay-productions-germany-launch-arno-schneppenheim-managing-director-1202306688/|title=Banijay Productions Germany Launches With Arno Schneppenheim As MD|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=1 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref> were created. Between 2017 and 2018, the business also launched four new scripted entities in the UK: BlackLight Television, Fearless Minds, Yellow Bird UK and Neon Ink, and acquired French-based Terence Films and Spanish Portocabo. Later, in 2019, with Bear Grylls and Delbert Shoopman, the group launched the Natural Studios and acquired Germany's Good Times.\n\nIn October 2018, Banijay entered advanced talks to acquire rival [[Endemol Shine Group]],<ref>https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/banijay-endemol-shine-advanced-talks-acquisition-1202968509</ref> with a deal approved a year later on October 26th, 2019.<ref>https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/banijay-buys-endemol-shine-stephane-courbit-marco-bassetti-sophie-turner-laing-1203380620/</ref>\n== Banijay Rights==\nOperating out of London, Paris and Copenhagen, Banijay Rights is Banijay Group's international division responsible for the distribution of its 22,000-hour strong catalogue of content across all genres. 50% of the catalogue is third-party programming from independent producers and networks throughout the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banijay.com/shows/|title=Our Shows - Banijay Group|website=www.banijay.com}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the merger of Banijay Group and Zodiak Media and that of their catalogues in February 2016, the division becomes Zodiak Rights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todotvnews.com/news/banijay-grup-merges-with-zodiac.html|title=Banijay Group Merges with Zodiak|first=|last=@todotvnews|website=Todotvnews}}</ref> In January 2017, Zodiak Rights was renamed Banijay Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2017/01/banijay-rebrands-zodiak-rights/699381/|title=Banijay rebrands Zodiak Rights \u2013 Page 699381 \u2013 TBI Vision|website=tbivision.com}}</ref> The company has been led by Tim Mutimer since February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2016/02/mutimer-run-sales-banijay-zodiak/551791/|title=Mutimer to run sales at Banijay-Zodiak \u2013 Page 551791 \u2013 TBI Vision|website=tbivision.com}}</ref>\n\n==Group companies==\nThe Banijay Group companies currently include the following:<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.banijay.com/companies/|publisher=Banijay Group|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Adventure Line Productions]] (France) \n*Air Productions (France) \n*Atlantis Film (Italy)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/11/08/banijay-merges-italian-prodcos-drymedia-and-magnolia-into-single-entity/|title=Banijay merges Italian prodcos DryMedia and Magnolia into single entity|website=Television Business International|date=8 November 2019|author=Richard Middleton}}</ref>\n*Aurora TV (Italy) \n*Banijay Asia\n*Banijay Finland \n*Banijay Italia (formed from merger of DRYMEDIA and Magnolia Italy)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/11/08/banijay-merges-italian-prodcos-drymedia-and-magnolia-into-single-entity/|title=Banijay merges Italian prodcos DryMedia and Magnolia into single entity|website=Television Business International|date=8 November 2019|author=Richard Middleton}}</ref>\n*Banijay Nordic Mobile<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/banijay-nordic-mobile/|title=Banijay Nordic Mobile|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Banijay Productions\n*Banijay Productions Germany\n*Banijay Studios France\n*Banijay Studios Italy\n*Banijay Studios North America \n*BlackLight (United Kingdom)\n*[[Brainpool TV|Brainpool]] (Germany) \n*[[Bunim/Murray Productions]] (United States)\n**[[Yellow Bird (company)#United States|Yellow Bird US]] (joint venture with [[Yellow Bird (company)|Yellow Bird]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/banijay-bunim-murray-yellow-bird-us-1202479614/|title=Banijay Moves Into U.S. Drama With Bunim/Murray & Yellow Bird JV; Sets Up Three Projects|website=[[Deadline (magazine)|deadline.com]]|language=English|author=Peter White|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> \n*Castaway Television Productions (United Kingdom)\n*[[The Comedy Unit]] (United Kingdom)\n*Cuarzo Producciones (Spain) \n*Dlo/Magnolia (Spain)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/dlo-producciones/|title=Dlo/Magnolia - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Fearless Minds (United Kingdom)\n*Funwood Media (Italy/Spain)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banijay.com/news/banijay-rights-acquires-funwood-media/|title=Banijay Rights Acquires Funwood Media|website=Banijay website}}</ref><ref>[http://deadline.com/2019/12/banijay-acquires-funwood-media-1202805359/ Banijay Acquires Italian & Spanish Drama Producer Funwood Media]</ref>\n*Good Times (Germany)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/good-times/|title=Good Times - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*H2O Productions (France) \n*ITV Movie (Italy)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/11/08/banijay-merges-italian-prodcos-drymedia-and-magnolia-into-single-entity/|title=Banijay merges Italian prodcos DryMedia and Magnolia into single entity|website=Television Business International|date=8 November 2019|author=Richard Middleton}}</ref>\n*IWC Media (United Kingdom) \n*Jarowskij (Sweden) \n*KM Production (France) \n*Mastiff Television (Denmark/Norway/Russia/Sweden)\n*The Natural Studios (United Kingdom; joint venture with Bear Grylls and Delbert Shoopman)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/the-natural-studios/|title=The Natural Studios - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Neon Ink Productions (United Kingdom)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/neon-ink/|title=Neon Ink Productions - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Nonpanic (Italy) \n*Non Stop People (24/7 celebrity news cable television channel; France/Spain)\n*[[Nordisk Film|Nordisk Film TV]] (Denmark/Norway/Sweden)\n*Pineapple Entertainment (Denmark) \n*Respirator (Denmark) \n*RDF Television (United Kingdom)<ref name=\"RDF Television - Banijay Group\">{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/rdf-television/|title=RDF Television - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n**Fizz (United Kingdom)<ref name=\"RDF Television - Banijay Group\"/>\n**RDF West (United Kingdom)<ref name=\"RDF Television - Banijay Group\"/>\n*[[Screentime]] (Australia)\n**Screentime New Zealand\n*Shauna Events (France)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/global/banijay-group-acquires-digital-company-shauna-events-1202673431/|title=Banijay Group Acquires Digital Company Shauna Events|website=variety.com}}</ref>\n*Sol (India) \n*Stephen David Entertainment (United States) \n*Terence Films (France)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/news/banijay-group-acquires-terence-films/|title=Banijay Group Acquires Terence Films|website=Banijay website|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n*Touchpaper Television (United Kingdom)\n*Wonder (United Kingdom)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/7wonder/|title=Wonder - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n**Little Wonder (United Kingdom)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/banijay-little-wonder-new-uk-production-banner-1202890778/|title=Banijay UK Launches New Label Little Wonder|website=variety.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wondertv.co.uk/littlewonder|title=LITTLE WONDER - Wonder|website=Wonder production company website}}</ref>\n*[[Yellow Bird (company)|Yellow Bird]] (Sweden) \n**[[Yellow Bird (company)#United Kingdom|Yellow Bird UK]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/news/banijays-yellow-bird-lands-uk/|title=Banijay's Yellow Bird lands in the United Kingdom|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n**[[Yellow Bird (company)#United States|Yellow Bird US]] (joint venture with [[Bunim/Murray Productions]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/banijay-bunim-murray-yellow-bird-us-1202479614/|title=Banijay Moves Into U.S. Drama With Bunim/Murray & Yellow Bird JV; Sets Up Three Projects|website=[[Deadline (magazine)|deadline.com]]|language=English|author=Peter White|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n*Zodiak Belgium\n*Zodiak Finland\n*Zodiak Kids (France/United Kingdom)\n*Zodiak Media Ireland  \n*Zodiak Nederland\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Key programmes==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genres !! Programmes\n|-\n| Entertainment || ''[[Fort Boyard (TV series)|Fort Boyard]]'', ''[[Don't Forget The Lyrics]]'', ''[[Popstars]]'', ''[[It's Only TV]]'', ''[[Beat The Star]]'', ''[[Wife Swap (UK TV series)|Wife Swap]]'', ''[[Undressed]]'', ''Making of the Mob'', ''[[Wild Things (TV series)|Wild Things]]'', ''All Against 1'', ''Stars in Danger''\n|-\n| Reality || ''[[Temptation Island (TV series)|Temptation Island]]'', ''[[Keeping Up With The Kardashians]]'', ''Party Workers'', ''[[71 Degrees North]]'', ''[[The Real World]]'', ''[[The Simple Life]]''\n|-\n| Kids || ''[[Martin Mystery]], [[Totally Spies!]]'', ''[[LoliRock]]'', ''[[Floogals]]'', ''Magiki''\n|-\n| Scripted || ''[[Versailles (TV series)|Versailles]]'', ''[[Okkupert|Occupied]]'', ''[[Wolf Creek (TV series)|Wolf Creek]]''\n|-\n| Factual || ''The Secret Life of 4 Year Olds''\n|}\n\n== Shareholders ==\nAt the time of its creation in 2008, Banijay Entertainment's shareholders, alongside St\u00e9phane Courbit (LOV Group),included: Groupe [[Bernard Arnault|Arnault]], AMS Industries and the [[Agnelli family|Agnelli]] and [[De Agostini]] families.\n\nAs of 2019, Banijay Group is controlled by a composed of St\u00e9phane Courbit's LOV Group through LDH (67%) with the remaining (33%) owned by [[Vivendi]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.banijay.com}}\n\n{{Vivendi}}\n\n[[Category:Media in Paris]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of France]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Banijay Group]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2013}}\n{{COI|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Banijay Group\n| logo = \n| former_name = Banijay Entertainment {{Small|(2008-2011)}}\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Entertainment]]\n| predecessor = [[Zodiak Media]] (2007-2016)\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2008}} in [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| founder = [[St\u00e9phane Courbit]]\n| location = \n| location_city = [[Paris]]\n| location_country = [[France]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = St\u00e9phane Courbit ([[Chairman]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Our People - Banijay Group|url=http://www.banijay.com/people|website=www.banijay.com|accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref><br>Marco Bassetti ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br>Peter Langenberg ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])<br />Marie Schweitzer (EVP Strategy and Business Development)<br> Sophie Kurinckx (Group CFO)<br> Nicolas Chazarain (Group Chief Legal Officer)\n| products = \n| owners = LDH (67%)<br>[[Vivendi]] (33%)\n| num_employees = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.banijay.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Banijay Group''' is a leading independent French global production and distribution business founded in January 2008 by [[St\u00e9phane Courbit]] as '''Banijay Entertainment'''. \n\nThrough its production entities and strategic partnerships, Banijay Group brings together creative entrepreneurs. Present in 16 territories across [[Europe]] ([[France]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Belgium]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Germany]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Sweden]], [[Denmark]], [[Norway]], [[Russia]] and [[Finland]]), the [[United States]], [[Asia]] (including [[India]]), [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]], the group's key formats and productions include Versailles, The Secret Life of 4 Year Olds, Temptation Island, Survivor, Keeping up with the Kardashians, The Real World, Fort Boyard, The Restaurant, Wife Swap, and Occupied.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banijay.com/|title=Banijay Group - We are Banijay|website=www.banijay.com}}</ref>\n\nBanijay's merger with [[Zodiak Media]], completed in February 2016, made the company the largest independent content producer in the world with revenues of around $1 billion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.televisionpost.com/news/banijay-zodiak-merge-to-create-worlds-largest-independent-production-company/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221105511/http://www.televisionpost.com/news/banijay-zodiak-merge-to-create-worlds-largest-independent-production-company/ |archive-date=2017-02-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Its catalogue of more than 22,000 hours of content across all genres, 50% of which is third-party programming from independent producers and networks, is distributed globally by Banijay Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todotvnews.com/news/Zodiak-Rights-Becomes-Banijay-Rights.html|title=Zodiak Rights Becomes Banijay Rights|first=|last=@todotvnews|website=Todotvnews}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.zodiakrights.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207131212/https://www.zodiakrights.com/ |archive-date=2017-02-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2019, the company announced it has entered into a definitive agreement to acquire 100% of the equity of [[Endemol Shine Group]], with its catalogue increasing to 85,000 hours of content across all genres and nearly 200 film and TV production companies.<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-26/banijay-to-acquire-black-mirror-producer-endemol-shine-group</ref> In February 2020, Banijay raised $2,600,000,000 in refinancing for acquiring Endemol Shine.<ref>https://deadline.com/2020/02/banijay-group-refinances-endemol-shine-group-takeover-1202856196/</ref>\n\nBanijay is chaired by St\u00e9phane Courbit and led by Marco Bassetti.\n==Acquisitions==\n\nBanijay Group (initially Banijay Entertainment), is the result of successive production company acquisitions and partnerships driven by French entrepreneur and TV producer, St\u00e9phane Courbit (LOV Group).\n\nIn October 2008, Banijay acquired Air Productions, the production company of famous French host [[Nagui]]. In 2009, Banijay made three acquisitions: 51% of Spanish production company Cuarzo Producciones on 12 January,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/9984/banijay-adquiere-el-51-del-accionariado-de-cuarzo-producciones/|title=Banijay adquiere el 51% del accionariado de Cuarzo Producciones|publisher=}}</ref> 50% of German producer [[Brainpool TV]] on 2 July<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/biz/news/banijay-buys-50-stake-in-brainpool-1118005629/|title=Banijay buys 50% stake in Brainpool|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=2 July 2009|publisher=}}</ref> and the entire television division of [[Copenhagen]]-based film studio [[Nordisk Film & TV]] on 12 October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/banijay-acquires-nordisk-films-tv-89927|title=Banijay acquires Nordisk Film's TV arm|publisher=}}</ref> In March 2010, Banijay acquired American production company [[Bunim/Murray Productions]] for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bunim-murray-acquired-frances-banijay-22026|title=Bunim-Murray acquired by France's Banijay|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Banijay acquired a majority stake in Australian production company [[Screentime]], which included a New Zealand division (Screentime New Zealand) and a 49% stake in Irish producer [[Shinawil]] which was sold in 2015.<ref>http://if.com.au/2012/09/04/article/Banijay-Group-acquires-majority-stake-in-Screentime/XWNVYNIBXL.html</ref> That same year, French 24/7 celebrity news television channel Non Stop People and popular French television host [[Cyril Hanouna]]'s H2O Productions became new members of the Group,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latribune.fr/technos-medias/medias/20120724trib000710651/stephane-courbit-rachete-la-societe-de-production-de-cyril-hanouna-et-boucle-le-rachat-d-everest-poker-.html|title=St\u00e9phane Courbit rach\u00e8te la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de production de Cyril Hanouna et boucle le rachat d'Everest Poker|publisher=}}</ref> followed in 2013 by Italian producer Ambra Multimedia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2013/04/marco-bassetti-named-ceo-of-banijay-group-acquires-italys-ambra-multimedia-485533/|title=Marco Bassetti Named CEO Of Banijay; Group Acquires Italy\u2019s Ambra Multimedia|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=29 April 2013|publisher=}}</ref> and Spanish independent producer, DLO Producciones.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/banijay-group-acquires-spanish-tv-625359|title=Banijay Group Acquires Spanish TV Production Firm DLO|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Banijay launched Banijay Studios North America in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/news/miptv-banijay-taps-former-endemol-exec-david-goldberg-to-launch-banijay-studios-north-america-1201153120/|title=MipTV: Banijay Taps David Goldberg to Launch Banijay Studios North America|first=Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=5 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref> On 9 January 2015, Banijay acquired Stephen David Entertainment, a [[New York City]]-based producer of television dramas and documentaries, expanding its North American presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/banijay-group-buys-controlling-share-in-stephen-david-entertainment-1201395774/|title=Banijay Group Buys Controlling Share in Stephen David Entertainment|first=Brian|last=Steinberg|date=8 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2015, Banijay Group announced that it would merge with [[Zodiak Media]], making the former the world's only largest television content production and distribution company not owned by a media conglomerate, as other large television content companies are ([[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]] is owned by [[Bertelsmann]] via [[RTL Group]], [[ITV Studios]] is owned by [[ITV plc]], [[Endemol Shine Group]] is a joint venture between [[The Walt Disney Company]] and [[Apollo Global Management]] and [[All3Media]] is a joint venture between [[John C. Malone]]-controlled companies [[Liberty Global]] and [[Discovery, Inc.]]). The merger was completed in February 2016.<ref>http://www.gruppodeagostini.it/(S(evycbiepmdyz4vyc3zd44nee))/paginaAllegati.aspx?IdAllegato=554</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/global/banijay-zodiak-to-merge-to-create-1-billion-production-house-1201549764/|title=Banijay, Zodiak to Merge to Create $1 Billion Production House|first=Leo Barraclough,Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=28 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Since then, Banijay Group continues to grow, both internally and externally.\n\nIn July 2017, Banijay Group acquired British producer Castaway Television Productions, the team behind global hit format, Survivor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/banijay-group-raises-416-million-castaway-survivor-acquisition-1202125847/|title=Banijay Raises $416M To Help Finance Acquisition Of \u2018Survivor\u2019s Castaway Prods|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=10 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In February 2018, it acquired another British producer, Wonder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/02/banijay-acquires-7wonder-production-arm.html|title=Banijay acquires Wonder production arm|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=28 February 2018|work=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, three new units, Banijay Studios Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/global/banijay-studios-italy-bows-to-produce-premium-scripted-content-1202856309/|title=Banijay Studios Italy Bows to Produce Premium Scripted Content|first=Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=25 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Banijay Asia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/banijay-rights-partners-deepak-dhar-launch-banijay-asia-1202747361/|title=Banijay Group Partners With Deepak Dhar to Launch Banijay Asia|first=Robert|last=Mitchell|date=9 April 2018|publisher=}}</ref> and Banijay Productions Germany,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/banijay-productions-germany-launch-arno-schneppenheim-managing-director-1202306688/|title=Banijay Productions Germany Launches With Arno Schneppenheim As MD|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=1 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref> were created. Between 2017 and 2018, the business also launched four new scripted entities in the UK: BlackLight Television, Fearless Minds, Yellow Bird UK and Neon Ink, and acquired French-based Terence Films and Spanish Portocabo. Later, in 2019, with Bear Grylls and Delbert Shoopman, the group launched the Natural Studios and acquired Germany's Good Times.\n\nIn October 2018, Banijay entered advanced talks to acquire rival [[Endemol Shine Group]],<ref>https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/banijay-endemol-shine-advanced-talks-acquisition-1202968509</ref> with a deal approved a year later on October 26th, 2019<ref>https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/banijay-buys-endemol-shine-stephane-courbit-marco-bassetti-sophie-turner-laing-1203380620/</ref>.\n== Banijay Rights==\nOperating out of London, Paris and Copenhagen, Banijay Rights is Banijay Group's international division responsible for the distribution of its 22,000-hour strong catalogue of content across all genres. 50% of the catalogue is third-party programming from independent producers and networks throughout the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banijay.com/shows/|title=Our Shows - Banijay Group|website=www.banijay.com}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the merger of Banijay Group and Zodiak Media and that of their catalogues in February 2016, the division becomes Zodiak Rights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todotvnews.com/news/banijay-grup-merges-with-zodiac.html|title=Banijay Group Merges with Zodiak|first=|last=@todotvnews|website=Todotvnews}}</ref> In January 2017, Zodiak Rights was renamed Banijay Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2017/01/banijay-rebrands-zodiak-rights/699381/|title=Banijay rebrands Zodiak Rights \u2013 Page 699381 \u2013 TBI Vision|website=tbivision.com}}</ref> The company has been led by Tim Mutimer since February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2016/02/mutimer-run-sales-banijay-zodiak/551791/|title=Mutimer to run sales at Banijay-Zodiak \u2013 Page 551791 \u2013 TBI Vision|website=tbivision.com}}</ref>\n\n==Group companies==\nThe Banijay Group companies currently include the following:<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.banijay.com/companies/|publisher=Banijay Group|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Adventure Line Productions]] (France) \n*Air Productions (France) \n*Atlantis Film (Italy)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/11/08/banijay-merges-italian-prodcos-drymedia-and-magnolia-into-single-entity/|title=Banijay merges Italian prodcos DryMedia and Magnolia into single entity|website=Television Business International|date=8 November 2019|author=Richard Middleton}}</ref>\n*Aurora TV (Italy) \n*Banijay Asia\n*Banijay Finland \n*Banijay Italia (formed from merger of DRYMEDIA and Magnolia Italy)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/11/08/banijay-merges-italian-prodcos-drymedia-and-magnolia-into-single-entity/|title=Banijay merges Italian prodcos DryMedia and Magnolia into single entity|website=Television Business International|date=8 November 2019|author=Richard Middleton}}</ref>\n*Banijay Nordic Mobile<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/banijay-nordic-mobile/|title=Banijay Nordic Mobile|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Banijay Productions\n*Banijay Productions Germany\n*Banijay Studios France\n*Banijay Studios Italy\n*Banijay Studios North America \n*BlackLight (United Kingdom)\n*[[Brainpool TV|Brainpool]] (Germany) \n*[[Bunim/Murray Productions]] (United States)\n**[[Yellow Bird (company)#United States|Yellow Bird US]] (joint venture with [[Yellow Bird (company)|Yellow Bird]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/banijay-bunim-murray-yellow-bird-us-1202479614/|title=Banijay Moves Into U.S. Drama With Bunim/Murray & Yellow Bird JV; Sets Up Three Projects|website=[[Deadline (magazine)|deadline.com]]|language=English|author=Peter White|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> \n*Castaway Television Productions (United Kingdom)\n*[[The Comedy Unit]] (United Kingdom)\n*Cuarzo Producciones (Spain) \n*Dlo/Magnolia (Spain)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/dlo-producciones/|title=Dlo/Magnolia - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Fearless Minds (United Kingdom)\n*Funwood Media (Italy/Spain)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banijay.com/news/banijay-rights-acquires-funwood-media/|title=Banijay Rights Acquires Funwood Media|website=Banijay website}}</ref><ref>[http://deadline.com/2019/12/banijay-acquires-funwood-media-1202805359/ Banijay Acquires Italian & Spanish Drama Producer Funwood Media]</ref>\n*Good Times (Germany)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/good-times/|title=Good Times - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*H2O Productions (France) \n*ITV Movie (Italy)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/11/08/banijay-merges-italian-prodcos-drymedia-and-magnolia-into-single-entity/|title=Banijay merges Italian prodcos DryMedia and Magnolia into single entity|website=Television Business International|date=8 November 2019|author=Richard Middleton}}</ref>\n*IWC Media (United Kingdom) \n*Jarowskij (Sweden) \n*KM Production (France) \n*Mastiff Television (Denmark/Norway/Russia/Sweden)\n*The Natural Studios (United Kingdom; joint venture with Bear Grylls and Delbert Shoopman)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/the-natural-studios/|title=The Natural Studios - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Neon Ink Productions (United Kingdom)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/neon-ink/|title=Neon Ink Productions - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n*Nonpanic (Italy) \n*Non Stop People (24/7 celebrity news cable television channel; France/Spain)\n*[[Nordisk Film|Nordisk Film TV]] (Denmark/Norway/Sweden)\n*Pineapple Entertainment (Denmark) \n*Respirator (Denmark) \n*RDF Television (United Kingdom)<ref name=\"RDF Television - Banijay Group\">{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/rdf-television/|title=RDF Television - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n**Fizz (United Kingdom)<ref name=\"RDF Television - Banijay Group\"/>\n**RDF West (United Kingdom)<ref name=\"RDF Television - Banijay Group\"/>\n*[[Screentime]] (Australia)\n**Screentime New Zealand\n*Shauna Events (France)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/global/banijay-group-acquires-digital-company-shauna-events-1202673431/|title=Banijay Group Acquires Digital Company Shauna Events|website=variety.com}}</ref>\n*Sol (India) \n*Stephen David Entertainment (United States) \n*Terence Films (France)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/news/banijay-group-acquires-terence-films/|title=Banijay Group Acquires Terence Films|website=Banijay website|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n*Touchpaper Television (United Kingdom)\n*Wonder (United Kingdom)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/company/7wonder/|title=Wonder - Banijay Group|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n**Little Wonder (United Kingdom)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/banijay-little-wonder-new-uk-production-banner-1202890778/|title=Banijay UK Launches New Label Little Wonder|website=variety.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wondertv.co.uk/littlewonder|title=LITTLE WONDER - Wonder|website=Wonder production company website}}</ref>\n*[[Yellow Bird (company)|Yellow Bird]] (Sweden) \n**[[Yellow Bird (company)#United Kingdom|Yellow Bird UK]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banijay.com/news/banijays-yellow-bird-lands-uk/|title=Banijay's Yellow Bird lands in the United Kingdom|website=Banijay website}}</ref>\n**[[Yellow Bird (company)#United States|Yellow Bird US]] (joint venture with [[Bunim/Murray Productions]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/banijay-bunim-murray-yellow-bird-us-1202479614/|title=Banijay Moves Into U.S. Drama With Bunim/Murray & Yellow Bird JV; Sets Up Three Projects|website=[[Deadline (magazine)|deadline.com]]|language=English|author=Peter White|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n*Zodiak Belgium\n*Zodiak Finland\n*Zodiak Kids (France/United Kingdom)\n*Zodiak Media Ireland  \n*Zodiak Nederland\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Key programmes==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genres !! Programmes\n|-\n| Entertainment || ''[[Fort Boyard (TV series)|Fort Boyard]]'', ''[[Don't Forget The Lyrics]]'', ''[[Popstars]]'', ''[[It's Only TV]]'', ''[[Beat The Star]]'', ''[[Wife Swap (UK TV series)|Wife Swap]]'', ''[[Undressed]]'', ''Making of the Mob'', ''[[Wild Things (TV series)|Wild Things]]'', ''All Against 1'', ''Stars in Danger''\n|-\n| Reality || ''[[Temptation Island (TV series)|Temptation Island]]'', ''[[Keeping Up With The Kardashians]]'', ''Party Workers'', ''[[71 Degrees North]]'', ''[[The Real World]]'', ''[[The Simple Life]]''\n|-\n| Kids || ''[[Martin Mystery]], [[Totally Spies!]]'', ''[[LoliRock]]'', ''[[Floogals]]'', ''Magiki''\n|-\n| Scripted || ''[[Versailles (TV series)|Versailles]]'', ''[[Okkupert|Occupied]]'', ''[[Wolf Creek (TV series)|Wolf Creek]]''\n|-\n| Factual || ''The Secret Life of 4 Year Olds''\n|}\n\n== Shareholders ==\nAt the time of its creation in 2008, Banijay Entertainment's shareholders, alongside St\u00e9phane Courbit (LOV Group),included: Groupe [[Bernard Arnault|Arnault]], AMS Industries and the [[Agnelli family|Agnelli]] and [[De Agostini]] families.\n\nAs of 2019, Banijay Group is controlled by a composed of St\u00e9phane Courbit's LOV Group through LDH (67%) with the remaining (33%) owned by [[Vivendi]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.banijay.com}}\n\n{{Vivendi}}\n\n[[Category:Media in Paris]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of France]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Banijay Group]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banijay_Group"}
{"title_page": "Mount Ascension", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Ascension\n| photo = Clouds that refused to lift over the mountains near Lost Lake (3866900178).jpg\n| photo_caption = Northeast aspect, summit on right\n| elevation_ft = 5710\n| elevation_ref = <ref>[https://listsofjohn.com/peak/143713 Ascension, Mount AK listsofjohn.com]</ref>\n| prominence_ft = 4810\n| prominence_ref= <ref name=peakbagger>{{cite peakbagger|pid=24028|name=Mount Ascension, Alaska|accessdate=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n| isolation_mi = 9.07\n| isolation_ref = <ref name=peakbagger/>\n| range = [[Kenai Mountains]]\n| parent_peak =\n| listing =\n| location = [[Chugach National Forest]]<br />[[Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Kenai Peninsula Borough]]<br />[[Alaska]], [[United States]]\n| map = USA Alaska\n| range_coordinates =\n| map_caption = Location of Mount Ascension in Alaska\n| label_position = left\n| coordinates = {{coord|60|15|33|N|149|29|45|W|type:mountain_region:US-AK_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] ''Seward B-7''\n| type =\n| first_ascent = 1968\n| easiest_route = [[Mountaineering]]\n}}\n\n'''Mount Ascension''' is a prominent {{convert|5710|ft|m|0|adj=on}} mountain summit located in the [[Kenai Mountains]], on the [[Kenai Peninsula]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]]. The mountain is situated in [[Chugach National Forest]], {{convert|6.8|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Mount Adair]], {{convert|3.5|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[Resurrection Peaks]], and {{convert|10|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[Seward, Alaska]]. The peak is near the mouth of [[Resurrection River]] into [[Resurrection Bay]]. The name ''Resurrection'', referring to the [[Resurrection of Jesus]], is overused for nearby landforms on the Kenai peninsula, as the mountain to the immediate south is Resurrection Peaks. This [[Ascension of Jesus|Ascension]] name is a variation of the theme.<ref name=\"gnis\"/> Mount Ascension's name was proposed in 1968 by the Mountaineering Club of Alaska, and officially adopted in 1969 by the [[United States Geological Survey]].<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=1420160|name=Mount Ascension|accessdate=2020-02-26}}</ref> Access to the peak is via the Lost Lake Trail, and mountaineering skills are needed to reach the summit. In clear weather the immense [[Harding Icefield]] can be seen from the top. The [[first ascent]] of this peak was made October 6, 1968, by John Vincent Hoeman and his wife, Dr. Grace (Jansen) Hoeman.<ref>The Alpine Journal: A Record of Mountain Adventure and Scientific Observation, Volume 74. page 240.</ref> \n\n==Climate==\nBased on the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Mount Ascension is located in a [[subarctic climate]] zone with long, cold, snowy winters, and mild summers.<ref name=Peel>{{cite journal | author = Peel, M. C. |author2=Finlayson, B. L. |author3=McMahon, T. A. |last-author-amp=yes | year = 2007 | title = Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen\u2212Geiger climate classification | journal = Hydrol. Earth Syst. Sci. | volume = 11 | issn = 1027-5606}}</ref> Temperatures can drop below \u221220 \u00b0C with wind chill factors below \u221230 \u00b0C. This climate supports a spruce and hemlock forest on the lower slopes.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Alaska|Mountains}}}}\n*[[List of mountain peaks of Alaska]]\n*[[Geology of Alaska]]\n\n==References==\n[[File:Kenai Lake with Mt. Ascension.jpg|thumb|220px|Mt. Ascension from Kenai Lake]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Mount Ascension [https://www.yr.no/place/United_States/Alaska/Mount_Ascension/ Weather forecast]\n* Mt. Ascension: [https://flickr.com/photos/dcsl/5913879077/in/photolist-a1Abdn-LptYG7-dcm3eS-aaqQRo-MPNXox-mU1Wc-qroV77-2bGZXqU-8Eg3rE-ho1MaH-5Qsdo9-2h9FXXj-5QSryc-oBwEDv-mU37K-4M5yH6-fiZbBH-6KTiFC-mU37M-owTZ52-bZCWfG-23395D1-yGeom2-goTYpH-ed1Buy-2aXFR9G-ebm15A-egSAof-5ArSZY-pMRYoh-dAauuC-dA51Uz-cDHffs-peCuyG-peowiv-ppMJCb-gJV7U9-URCrgm-yoRZ67-86os6y-7qZrKi-64AhLN-egSAv1-egUMJP-6nqU5L-HE9VAj-JaADsY-JaAPN7-yFtMyB-eh1xE1 Flickr photo]\n* Mt. Ascension in winter: [https://flickr.com/photos/dcsl/3042286485/in/photolist-fa4aZU-5YNvWT-a1Abdn-iZYQDN-a9eBQK-61ei6m-5YkAsN-5XjRmc-5ZwAg9-65iXUS-619uqg-5AY6fz-ujgX9h-tNXnHw-tP87Bi-u3cPPP-cw4MsL-cVNAm-5STzUo-5CQvMg-5KV6s7-7cetsT-7b3q48-b5rqnZ-7bhtXM-5YfgdV-7awNAm-6LYHHa-7bm8bW-6M5eqs-6Mffx5-6M1oRM-6MiJjq-6LZ6EF-6M5329-71SzPN-7FDScC-7cjfMJ-7FDSVG-tnD6zW-uhk1GE-u35dim-tnP1NF-u35tRh-tnPKL4-u3cXo6-ujgTkL-v2WShE-tnNT78-ujRxmD Flickr photo]\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Alaska|Ascension]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Ascension]]\n[[Category:Kenai Mountains-Turnagain Arm National Heritage Area|Ascension]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Ascension\n| photo = Clouds that refused to lift over the mountains near Lost Lake (3866900178).jpg\n| photo_caption = Northeast aspect, summit on right\n| elevation_ft = 5710\n| elevation_ref = <ref>[https://listsofjohn.com/peak/143713 Ascension, Mount AK listsofjohn.com]</ref>\n| prominence_ft = 4810\n| prominence_ref= <ref name=peakbagger>{{cite peakbagger|pid=24028|name=Mount Ascension, Alaska|accessdate=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n| isolation_mi = 9.07\n| isolation_ref = <ref name=peakbagger/>\n| range = [[Kenai Mountains]]\n| parent_peak =\n| listing =\n| location = [[Chugach National Forest]]<br />[[Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Kenai Peninsula Borough]]<br />[[Alaska]], [[United States]]\n| map = USA Alaska\n| range_coordinates =\n| map_caption = Location of Mount Ascension in Alaska\n| label_position = left\n| coordinates = {{coord|60|15|33|N|149|29|45|W|type:mountain_region:US-AK_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] ''Seward B-7''\n| type =\n| first_ascent = 1968\n| easiest_route = [[Mountaineering]]\n}}\n\n'''Mount Ascension''' is a prominent {{convert|5710|ft|m|0|adj=on}} mountain summit located in the [[Kenai Mountains]], on the [[Kenai Peninsula]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]]. The mountain is situated in [[Chugach National Forest]], {{convert|6.8|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Mount Adair]], {{convert|3.5|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[Resurrection Peaks]], and {{convert|10|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[Seward, Alaska]]. The peak is near the mouth of [[Resurrection River]] into [[Resurrection Bay]]. The name ''Resurrection'', referring to the [[Resurrection of Jesus]], is overused for nearby landforms on the Kenai peninsula, as the mountain to the immediate south is Resurrection Peaks. This [[Ascension of Jesus|Ascension]] name is a variation of the theme.<ref name=\"gnis\"/> Mount Ascension's name was proposed in 1968 by the Mountaineering Club of Alaska, and officially adopted in 1969 by the [[United States Geological Survey]].<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=1420160|name=Mount Ascension|accessdate=2020-02-26}}</ref> Access to the peak is via the Lost Lake Trail, and mountaineering skills are needed to reach the summit. In clear weather the immense [[Harding Icefield]] can be seen from the top. The [[first ascent]] of this peak was made October 6, 1968, by John Vincent Hoeman and his wife, Dr. Grace (Jansen) Hoeman.<ref>The Alpine Journal: A Record of Mountain Adventure and Scientific Observation, Volume 74. page 240.</ref> \n\n==Climate==\nBased on the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Mount Ascension is located in a [[subarctic climate]] zone with long, cold, snowy winters, and mild summers.<ref name=Peel>{{cite journal | author = Peel, M. C. |author2=Finlayson, B. L. |author3=McMahon, T. A. |last-author-amp=yes | year = 2007 | title = Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen\u2212Geiger climate classification | journal = Hydrol. Earth Syst. Sci. | volume = 11 | issn = 1027-5606}}</ref> Temperatures can drop below \u221220 \u00b0C with wind chill factors below \u221230 \u00b0C. This climate supports a spruce and hemlock forest on the lower slopes.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Alaska|Mountains}}}}\n*[[List of mountain peaks of Alaska]]\n*[[Geology of Alaska]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[File:Kenai Lake with Mt. Ascension.jpg|thumb|220px|Mt. Ascension from Kenai Lake]]\n==External links==\n* Mount Ascension [https://www.yr.no/place/United_States/Alaska/Mount_Ascension/ Weather forecast]\n* Mt. Ascension: [https://flickr.com/photos/dcsl/5913879077/in/photolist-a1Abdn-LptYG7-dcm3eS-aaqQRo-MPNXox-mU1Wc-qroV77-2bGZXqU-8Eg3rE-ho1MaH-5Qsdo9-2h9FXXj-5QSryc-oBwEDv-mU37K-4M5yH6-fiZbBH-6KTiFC-mU37M-owTZ52-bZCWfG-23395D1-yGeom2-goTYpH-ed1Buy-2aXFR9G-ebm15A-egSAof-5ArSZY-pMRYoh-dAauuC-dA51Uz-cDHffs-peCuyG-peowiv-ppMJCb-gJV7U9-URCrgm-yoRZ67-86os6y-7qZrKi-64AhLN-egSAv1-egUMJP-6nqU5L-HE9VAj-JaADsY-JaAPN7-yFtMyB-eh1xE1 Flickr photo]\n* Mt. Ascension in winter: [https://flickr.com/photos/dcsl/3042286485/in/photolist-fa4aZU-5YNvWT-a1Abdn-iZYQDN-a9eBQK-61ei6m-5YkAsN-5XjRmc-5ZwAg9-65iXUS-619uqg-5AY6fz-ujgX9h-tNXnHw-tP87Bi-u3cPPP-cw4MsL-cVNAm-5STzUo-5CQvMg-5KV6s7-7cetsT-7b3q48-b5rqnZ-7bhtXM-5YfgdV-7awNAm-6LYHHa-7bm8bW-6M5eqs-6Mffx5-6M1oRM-6MiJjq-6LZ6EF-6M5329-71SzPN-7FDScC-7cjfMJ-7FDSVG-tnD6zW-uhk1GE-u35dim-tnP1NF-u35tRh-tnPKL4-u3cXo6-ujgTkL-v2WShE-tnNT78-ujRxmD Flickr photo]\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Alaska|Ascension]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Ascension]]\n[[Category:Kenai Mountains-Turnagain Arm National Heritage Area|Ascension]]\n", "name_user": "Ron Clausen", "label": "safe", "comment": "format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Ascension"}
{"title_page": "Bangladesh Chhatra League", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name= Bangladesh Chhatra League\n| native_name= \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997\n| abbreviation = BCL\n| colorcode= Green\n| logo= Bangladesh Chhatra League official logo.webp\n| caption= Badge\n| flag =  \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be.svg\n| leader =\n| president = Al Nahean Khan Joy <ref>{{cite news |title=\u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997 \u09a5\u09c7\u0995\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u09a6 \u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8 -\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09a8\u09c0, \u09a6\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac\u09c7 \u099c\u09af\u09bc-\u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u0995 |url= https://prothomalo.com/bangladesh/article/1614357/\u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997-\u09a5\u09c7\u0995\u09c7-\u09ac\u09be\u09a6-\u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8-\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09a8\u09c0-\u09a6\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac\u09c7-\u099c\u09af\u09bc-\u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u0995 |accessdate=14 September 2019 |work=Prothom Alo}}</ref>\n| chairperson =\n| chairman =\n| general_secretary= Lekhak Bhattacharjee \n| treasurer =\n| spokesperson =\n| founder= [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n| founded={{start date and age|4th|January|1948|df=yes}}\n| membership =\n| ideology =\n| international =\n| national =\n| newspaper =\n| headquarters = 23, Bangabondhu Avenue, Gulistan, Dhaka- 1000\n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = [[Bangladesh Awami League]]\n| website = {{URL|bsl.org.bd}}\n| country = Bangladesh\n}}\n\nThe '''Bangladesh Chhatra League''' ({{lang-bn| \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997; [[translation]]: Bangladesh Students' League}}; {{small|abbr.}} '''BCL'''), formerly known as the '''East Pakistan Student League''', often simply called the '''Chhatra League''', is a students' [[political organisation]] in [[Bangladesh]], founded by [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] on 4 January 1948. BCL is the student wing of the [[Bangladesh Awami League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-45069935|title=Bangladesh students attacked during Dhaka protest |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nBCL has been repeatedly accused of using torture, extortion, violence, and killings to instill fear.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/10/father-demands-justice-after-beating-to-death-of-student-in-dhaka|title=Father demands justice after student beaten to death in Bangladesh|last=Delhi|first=Redwan Ahmed Rebecca Ratcliffe in|date=2019-10-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-49979097|title=Killing of Bangladesh student triggers protests|date=2019-10-08|access-date=2019-10-17|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/south-central-asia/bangladesh-student-killing-sparks-university-protests|title=Bangladesh Student Killing Sparks University Protests|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> At least 33 people were killed and 1,500 got seriously injured from attacks by BCL between 2009 and 2014. Number of fatalities rose to 129 between 2014 and 2018 while 31 people were killed in 2018 alone.<ref>{{cite news |title=TERROR RISING |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/spotlight/news/terror-rising-1811842 |accessdate=25 December 2019 |agency=The Daily Star}}</ref> Following the attacks on [[2018 Bangladesh road-safety protests|student protesters]] in 2018, a petition was started by general people of Bangladesh to \"Enlist Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) as a Terrorist Organization\" at [[Change.org]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Awami League / Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) |url=https://www.trackingterrorism.org/group/awami-league-bangladesh-chhatra-league-bcl |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.democracynewslive.com/world/bloody-sunday-in-bangladesh-506603|title=Bloody Sunday in Bangladesh|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/ap4Zw|title=P\u00e9tition \u00b7 Enlist Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) as a Terrorist Orga\u2026|date=2019-10-14|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> In 2019, prominent English language daily of Bangladesh, [[Dhaka Tribune]] labelled the organization as \"the brand of shame\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The brand of shame that is Chhatra League|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2019/10/10/the-brand-of-shame-that-is-chhatra-league-murders-brutality-arson-and-controversies-aplenty |accessdate=11 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOn 4 January 1948, the East Pakistan Muslim Chhatra League was established by Sheikh Mujibur Rahman at a meeting in [[Fazlul Huq Muslim Hall]] at the [[University of Dhaka]]. The organisation's name was later changed{{when|date=August 2018}} to the Bangladesh Chhatra League. Naeemuddin Ahmed was the first convener of BCL,{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} while Khalek Newaz Khan was the founder general secretary of the Chhatra League.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nDuring the 1971 [[Bangladesh Liberation War]], members of the Chhatra League were recruited into the [[Mujib Bahini]] (also known as the Bengal Liberation Force),{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} an armed group trained by India's foreign intelligence agency, the [[Research and Analysis Wing]]. However, their exact involvement in the war is disputed, with [[Zafrullah Chowdhury]] stating, \"The Mujib Bahini did not fight the liberation war.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahmed |first1=Taib |last2=Islam |first2=Khadimul |date=16 December 2014 |title='Mujib Bahini didn't fight liberation war' |url=http://newagebd.net/77152/mujib-bahini-didnt-fight-liberation-war/#sthash.ZMNsQNLM.dpbs |newspaper=The New Age |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> In 2014, [[A. K. Khandker]] was sued for accusing the Mujib Bahini of hooliganism and looting during the war in his book in his book ''1971: Bhetore Baire''.<ref>{{cite news |title=AK Khandker sued for 'Mujib Bahini's looting' claim |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/ak-khandker-sued-for-mujib-bahinis-looting-claim-41063 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Violence ==\n=== Murder of Abrar Fahad ===\n{{main article|Murder of Abrar Fahad}}\nA student of [[Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology]] was beaten to death after Bangladesh Chhatra League men allegedly questioned him suspecting his involvement with Shibir.<ref>{{cite news |title=Buet student murdered after \u2018BCL men grilled\u2019 him |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/buet-student-found-dead-dormitory-1810519 |accessdate=8 October 2019 |publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/spotlight/news/terror-rising-1811842|title=TERROR RISING|date=2019-10-11|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/dhaka/2019/10/09/four-hours-of-torture-led-to-abrar-s-death|title=Four hours of torture led to Abrar's death|date=2019-10-09|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nAlleged students are: Mehedi Hasan Rasel of civil engineering, general secretary of Buet BCL, Muhtasim Fuad of civil engineering vice-president, Mehedi Hasan Robein of chemical engineering, the organizing secretary, Anik Sarker of mechanical engineering, the secretary of information and research affairs, Ishtiaq Ahmed Munna of mechanical engineering, the publication affairs secretary, Ifti Mosharraf Shakal of biomedical engineering batch-16, the deputy social welfare secretary, Meftahul Islam Zion of naval architecture and marine engineering, the sports secretary, Muzahidur Rahman Muzahid of civil engineering, Muntasir Alam Jemi of chemical engineering and Khandaker Tabakhkharul Islam Tanvir of mechanical engineering, Moniruzzaman Monir, Water Resources Engineering Department, Akash Hossain, Civil Engineering Department and Shamsul Arefin Rafat, Mechanical Engineering Department of Buet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abrar murder: 3 more Buet students arrested |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/10-remanded-buet-student-abrar-murder-case-1810987 |accessdate=8 October 2019 |publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\n=== Harassment of women in Dhaka University campus on Pohela Boishakh 2015 ===\nOn Bangla New Year celebration of Dhaka University campus, a group of students sexually assaulted women on the venue and tried to strip them off their clothing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2015/04/15/boishakh-celebration-women-harassed-near-tsc|title=Boishakh celebration: Women harassed near TSC|date=2015-04-15|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Law enforcement was present in the vicinity, yet the miscreants were not stopped, according to witness accounts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/outrage-over-sex-assault-77496|title=Outrage over sex assault|date=2015-04-16|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>:<blockquote>\"When we sought help from a few policemen standing 20 yards from the spot, they said that the area was beyond their jurisdiction,\u201d said Amit who also came under attack by the youths and had his fingers fractured.\n\nAmit along with five of his fellow activists had tried to save a group of women aged between 25-30 years from the rowdy youths.\n\n\"The youths were divided into three groups and each group had 10-12 of them. People everywhere around were blowing vuvuzela so loudly that nobody could hear the victims' cry for help,\" he said, adding thousands of people were milling around the area, making it difficult for them to prevent the attackers.</blockquote>Despite having CCTV footage which clearly identified the culprits, the police made no arrests by 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/court/2019/04/14/4-years-on-no-progress-in-pohela-boishakh-sexual-harassment-trial|title=4 years on, no progress in Pohela Boishakh sexual harassment trial|date=2019-04-14|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>:<blockquote>The probe over the incident was forced to end as the DB police failed to concretely identify any of the culprits beyond simple facial and visual CCTV recording during their eight-month-long investigation. DB Sub inspector Dipok Kumar Das submitted a final report to court on December 13, 2015, saying he had failed to identify any of the suspects.</blockquote>As the ruling party Awami League has control over law enforcement and Chhatra League is the student wing of Awami League, it is widely speculated that the police assisted Chhatra League to carry out these attacks by taking no action to stop them and by making no arrests. Notably, Chhatra League also prevented its female members from protesting this incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2015/04/19/chhatra-league-reins-in-its-women|title=Chhatra League reins in its women|date=2015-04-19|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Murder of Biswajit Das ===\n{{Main|Murder of Biswajit Das}}\nBiswajit Das, a 24-year-old tailor in [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh, was murdered on 9 December 2012 by members of the Bangladesh Chhatra League who mistook Das for an opposition supporter. Das was chased and attacked with [[machete]]s, iron bars, and hockey sticks.<ref name=\"ds3Jun2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news/21-bcl-men-indicted|title=21 BCL men indicted|date=3 June 2013|newspaper=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> He was taken to [[Mitford Hospital, Dhaka|Mitford Hospital]], where he shortly died of his wounds.<ref name=\"bdn18Dec2013\">{{cite news|url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2013/12/18/eight-to-die-for-biswajit-murder|title=Eight to die for Biswajit murder, 13 get life|date=18 December 2013|newspaper=bdnews24.com|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> Twenty-one BCL activists were found guilty of murder on 18 December 2013. Eight were sentenced to death and thirteen were sentenced to life in prison.<ref name=\"livemint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/jmtTMbVQ4hRsD3YibeglWO/Bangladesh-sentences-eight-students-to-death-for-murder.html|title=Bangladesh sentences eight students to death for murder|date=18 December 2013|newspaper=[[LiveMint]]|access-date=2017-08-03|agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> Only eight of the twenty-one defendants were in custody at the time of the sentence, with the remaining thirteen tried in absentia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-25431557|title=Bangladesh sentences eight students to death for murder|date=18 December 2013|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/8-awami-activists-get-death-for-murder-of-hindu-man/article5474260.ece|title=8 Awami activists get death for murder of Hindu man|date=18 December 2013|newspaper=The Hindu|access-date=2017-01-29|agency=PTI}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 conflicts ===\nIn March 2018, a student of [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]] (SUST) suffered a bullet wound during a clash between two BCL factions.<ref name=\"student_shot_2018_03_21_theindependentbd_com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/142409|title=Student shot during BCL infighting at SUST|date=21 March 2018|work=The Independent |location=Dhaka |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Reportedly, two factions of the SUST unit of BCL, led by vice-presidents of the unit, had battled over establishing supremacy on the campus. A group of BCL men, led by Akando and colleagues, attacked another man in a restaurant near the university. The man responded with a gunshot which injured another student.<ref name=\"student_shot_2018_03_21_theindependentbd_com\" />\n\nIn July 2018, protests and counter-violence erupted at various universities, particularly [[Rajshahi University]], over the [[Bangladesh Quota Reform Protests 2018|quota reform movement]], which sought to change the quota system that allocated 56% of Bangladesh government jobs to specific classes. In a protest procession on 2 July 2018, quota-reform movement leader Toriqul Islam and 15 others were attacked with sticks, bamboo poles, a dagger and a hammer. Islam's leg was broken as a result of the attack. A correspondent from ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'' filmed the incident and the newspaper reported that it had identified eleven of the attackers, stating that ten were members of the BCL.<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_dailystar_net\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/rajshahi-police-saw-nothing-1602220|title=Rajshahi police saw nothing!|date=9 July 2018 |work=The Daily Star |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"injured_quota_protester_2018_07_08_dhaka_tribune\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/07/08/injured-quota-reform-activist-tariqul-being-moved-to-dhaka-for-treatment|title=Injured quota protester Tariqul moved to Dhaka|date=8 July 2018|work=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Video and photos of the attack circulated on social media, prompting criticism over police and university administration inaction.<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_dailystar_net\" />\n\n==== Dhaka bus protests ====\n{{Main|2018 Bangladesh road safety protests}}\nOn 29 July 2018, two students were killed and a further twelve people were injured when a bus hit a bus stop in Dhaka. Protests began shortly afterwards, demanding better road safety. During the protests, BCL members were alleged to have been involved in numerous attacks on protestors throughout Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/dhaka/2018/08/04/live-students-block-streets-in-uttara|title=Minute by minute: Saturday\u2019s protest ends with violence in Jigatola |date=4 August 2018 |work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref> On 5 August 2018, a number of photojournalists were attacked, allegedly by members of the BCL wearing helmets. Law enforcement officers were present but did not make any attempt to stop the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/5-photojournalists-hurt-in-bcl-men-attack-science-lab-dhaka-student-protest-for-safe-roads-1616251|title=5 photojournalists hurt in \u2018BCL attack\u2019 |date=5 August 2018 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-08-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/160959|title=6 photojournalists injured in attacks by \u2018BCL\u2019 |date=5 August 2018|newspaper=The Independent|location=Bangladesh|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of student organizations in Bangladesh]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bangladesh Awami League}}\n\n[[Category:Student organisations in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Student wings of political parties in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Awami League]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi student movements]]\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1948]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name= Bangladesh Chhatra League\n| native_name= \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997\n| abbreviation = BCL\n| colorcode= Green\n| logo= Bangladesh Chhatra League official logo.webp\n| caption= Badge\n| flag =  \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be.svg\n| leader =\n| president = Al Nahean Khan Joy <ref>{{cite news |title=\u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997 \u09a5\u09c7\u0995\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u09a6 \u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8 -\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09a8\u09c0, \u09a6\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac\u09c7 \u099c\u09af\u09bc-\u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u0995 |url= https://prothomalo.com/bangladesh/article/1614357/\u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997-\u09a5\u09c7\u0995\u09c7-\u09ac\u09be\u09a6-\u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8-\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09a8\u09c0-\u09a6\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac\u09c7-\u099c\u09af\u09bc-\u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u0995 |accessdate=14 September 2019 |work=Prothom Alo}}</ref>\n| chairperson =\n| chairman =\n| general_secretary= Lekhak Bhattacharjee \n| treasurer =\n| spokesperson =\n| founder= [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n| founded={{start date and age|4th|January|1948|df=yes}}\n| membership =\n| ideology =\n| international =\n| national =\n| newspaper =\n| headquarters = 23, Bangabondhu Avenue, Gulistan, Dhaka- 1000\n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = [[Bangladesh Awami League]]\n| website = {{URL|bsl.org.bd}}\n| country = Bangladesh\n}}\n\nThe '''Bangladesh Chhatra League''' ({{lang-bn| \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099b\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b2\u09c0\u0997; [[translation]]: Bangladesh Students' League}}; {{small|abbr.}} '''BCL'''), formerly known as the '''East Pakistan Student League''', often simply called the '''Chhatra League''', is a students' [[political organisation]] in [[Bangladesh]], founded by [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] on 4 January 1948. BCL is the student wing of the [[Bangladesh Awami League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-45069935|title=Bangladesh students attacked during Dhaka protest |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nBCL has been repeatedly accused of using torture, extortion, violence, and killings to instill fear.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/10/father-demands-justice-after-beating-to-death-of-student-in-dhaka|title=Father demands justice after student beaten to death in Bangladesh|last=Delhi|first=Redwan Ahmed Rebecca Ratcliffe in|date=2019-10-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-49979097|title=Killing of Bangladesh student triggers protests|date=2019-10-08|access-date=2019-10-17|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/south-central-asia/bangladesh-student-killing-sparks-university-protests|title=Bangladesh Student Killing Sparks University Protests|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> At least 33 people were killed and 1,500 got seriously injured from attacks by BCL between 2009 and 2014. Number of fatalities rose to 129 between 2014 and 2018 while 31 people were killed in 2018 alone.<ref>{{cite news |title=TERROR RISING |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/spotlight/news/terror-rising-1811842 |accessdate=25 December 2019 |agency=The Daily Star}}</ref> Following the attacks on [[2018 Bangladesh road-safety protests|student protesters]] in 2018, a petition was started by general people of Bangladesh to \"Enlist Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) as a Terrorist Organization\" at [[Change.org]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Awami League / Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) |url=https://www.trackingterrorism.org/group/awami-league-bangladesh-chhatra-league-bcl |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.democracynewslive.com/world/bloody-sunday-in-bangladesh-506603|title=Bloody Sunday in Bangladesh|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/ap4Zw|title=P\u00e9tition \u00b7 Enlist Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) as a Terrorist Orga\u2026|date=2019-10-14|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> In 2019, prominent English language daily of Bangladesh, [[Dhaka Tribune]] labelled the organization as \"the brand of shame\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The brand of shame that is Chhatra League|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2019/10/10/the-brand-of-shame-that-is-chhatra-league-murders-brutality-arson-and-controversies-aplenty |accessdate=11 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOn 4 January 1948, the East Pakistan Muslim Chhatra League was established by Sheikh Mujibur Rahman at a meeting in [[Fazlul Huq Muslim Hall]] at the [[University of Dhaka]]. The organisation's name was later changed{{when|date=August 2018}} to the Bangladesh Chhatra League. Naeemuddin Ahmed was the first convener of BCL,{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} while Khalek Newaz Khan was the founder general secretary of the Chhatra League.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nDuring the 1971 [[Bangladesh Liberation War]], members of the Chhatra League were recruited into the [[Mujib Bahini]] (also known as the Bengal Liberation Force),{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} an armed group trained by India's foreign intelligence agency, the [[Research and Analysis Wing]]. However, their exact involvement in the war is disputed, with [[Zafrullah Chowdhury]] stating, \"The Mujib Bahini did not fight the liberation war.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahmed |first1=Taib |last2=Islam |first2=Khadimul |date=16 December 2014 |title='Mujib Bahini didn't fight liberation war' |url=http://newagebd.net/77152/mujib-bahini-didnt-fight-liberation-war/#sthash.ZMNsQNLM.dpbs |newspaper=The New Age |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> In 2014, [[A. K. Khandker]] was sued for accusing the Mujib Bahini of hooliganism and looting during the war in his book in his book ''1971: Bhetore Baire''.<ref>{{cite news |title=AK Khandker sued for 'Mujib Bahini's looting' claim |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/ak-khandker-sued-for-mujib-bahinis-looting-claim-41063 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Violence ==\n=== Murder of Abrar Fahad ===\n{{main article|Murder of Abrar Fahad}}\nA student of [[Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology]] was beaten to death after Bangladesh Chhatra League men allegedly questioned him suspecting his involvement with Shibir.<ref>{{cite news |title=Buet student murdered after \u2018BCL men grilled\u2019 him |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/buet-student-found-dead-dormitory-1810519 |accessdate=8 October 2019 |publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/spotlight/news/terror-rising-1811842|title=TERROR RISING|date=2019-10-11|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/dhaka/2019/10/09/four-hours-of-torture-led-to-abrar-s-death|title=Four hours of torture led to Abrar's death|date=2019-10-09|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nAlleged students are: Mehedi Hasan Rasel of civil engineering, general secretary of Buet BCL, Muhtasim Fuad of civil engineering vice-president, Mehedi Hasan Robein of chemical engineering, the organizing secretary, Anik Sarker of mechanical engineering, the secretary of information and research affairs, Ishtiaq Ahmed Munna of mechanical engineering, the publication affairs secretary, Ifti Mosharraf Shakal of biomedical engineering batch-16, the deputy social welfare secretary, Meftahul Islam Zion of naval architecture and marine engineering, the sports secretary, Muzahidur Rahman Muzahid of civil engineering, Muntasir Alam Jemi of chemical engineering and Khandaker Tabakhkharul Islam Tanvir of mechanical engineering, Moniruzzaman Monir, Water Resources Engineering Department, Akash Hossain, Civil Engineering Department and Shamsul Arefin Rafat, Mechanical Engineering Department of Buet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abrar murder: 3 more Buet students arrested |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/10-remanded-buet-student-abrar-murder-case-1810987 |accessdate=8 October 2019 |publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\n=== Harassment of women in Dhaka University campus on Pohela Boishakh 2015 ===\nOn Bangla New Year celebration of Dhaka University campus, a group of students sexually assaulted women on the venue and tried to strip them off their clothing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2015/04/15/boishakh-celebration-women-harassed-near-tsc|title=Boishakh celebration: Women harassed near TSC|date=2015-04-15|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>. Law enforcement was present in the vicinity, yet the miscreants were not stopped, according to witness accounts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/outrage-over-sex-assault-77496|title=Outrage over sex assault|date=2015-04-16|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>:<blockquote>\"When we sought help from a few policemen standing 20 yards from the spot, they said that the area was beyond their jurisdiction,\u201d said Amit who also came under attack by the youths and had his fingers fractured.\n\nAmit along with five of his fellow activists had tried to save a group of women aged between 25-30 years from the rowdy youths.\n\n\"The youths were divided into three groups and each group had 10-12 of them. People everywhere around were blowing vuvuzela so loudly that nobody could hear the victims' cry for help,\" he said, adding thousands of people were milling around the area, making it difficult for them to prevent the attackers.</blockquote>Despite having CCTV footage which clearly identified the culprits, the police made no arrests by 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/court/2019/04/14/4-years-on-no-progress-in-pohela-boishakh-sexual-harassment-trial|title=4 years on, no progress in Pohela Boishakh sexual harassment trial|date=2019-04-14|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>:<blockquote>The probe over the incident was forced to end as the DB police failed to concretely identify any of the culprits beyond simple facial and visual CCTV recording during their eight-month-long investigation. DB Sub inspector Dipok Kumar Das submitted a final report to court on December 13, 2015, saying he had failed to identify any of the suspects.</blockquote>As the ruling party Awami League has control over law enforcement and Chhatra League is the student wing of Awami League, it is widely speculated that the police assisted Chhatra League to carry out these attacks by taking no action to stop them and by making no arrests. Notably, Chhatra League also prevented its female members from protesting this incident<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2015/04/19/chhatra-league-reins-in-its-women|title=Chhatra League reins in its women|date=2015-04-19|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>.\n\n=== Murder of Biswajit Das ===\n{{Main|Murder of Biswajit Das}}\nBiswajit Das, a 24-year-old tailor in [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh, was murdered on 9 December 2012 by members of the Bangladesh Chhatra League who mistook Das for an opposition supporter. Das was chased and attacked with [[machete]]s, iron bars, and hockey sticks.<ref name=\"ds3Jun2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news/21-bcl-men-indicted|title=21 BCL men indicted|date=3 June 2013|newspaper=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> He was taken to [[Mitford Hospital, Dhaka|Mitford Hospital]], where he shortly died of his wounds.<ref name=\"bdn18Dec2013\">{{cite news|url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2013/12/18/eight-to-die-for-biswajit-murder|title=Eight to die for Biswajit murder, 13 get life|date=18 December 2013|newspaper=bdnews24.com|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> Twenty-one BCL activists were found guilty of murder on 18 December 2013. Eight were sentenced to death and thirteen were sentenced to life in prison.<ref name=\"livemint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/jmtTMbVQ4hRsD3YibeglWO/Bangladesh-sentences-eight-students-to-death-for-murder.html|title=Bangladesh sentences eight students to death for murder|date=18 December 2013|newspaper=[[LiveMint]]|access-date=2017-08-03|agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> Only eight of the twenty-one defendants were in custody at the time of the sentence, with the remaining thirteen tried in absentia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-25431557|title=Bangladesh sentences eight students to death for murder|date=18 December 2013|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/8-awami-activists-get-death-for-murder-of-hindu-man/article5474260.ece|title=8 Awami activists get death for murder of Hindu man|date=18 December 2013|newspaper=The Hindu|access-date=2017-01-29|agency=PTI}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 conflicts ===\nIn March 2018, a student of [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]] (SUST) suffered a bullet wound during a clash between two BCL factions.<ref name=\"student_shot_2018_03_21_theindependentbd_com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/142409|title=Student shot during BCL infighting at SUST|date=21 March 2018|work=The Independent |location=Dhaka |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Reportedly, two factions of the SUST unit of BCL, led by vice-presidents of the unit, had battled over establishing supremacy on the campus. A group of BCL men, led by Akando and colleagues, attacked another man in a restaurant near the university. The man responded with a gunshot which injured another student.<ref name=\"student_shot_2018_03_21_theindependentbd_com\" />\n\nIn July 2018, protests and counter-violence erupted at various universities, particularly [[Rajshahi University]], over the [[Bangladesh Quota Reform Protests 2018|quota reform movement]], which sought to change the quota system that allocated 56% of Bangladesh government jobs to specific classes. In a protest procession on 2 July 2018, quota-reform movement leader Toriqul Islam and 15 others were attacked with sticks, bamboo poles, a dagger and a hammer. Islam's leg was broken as a result of the attack. A correspondent from ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'' filmed the incident and the newspaper reported that it had identified eleven of the attackers, stating that ten were members of the BCL.<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_dailystar_net\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/rajshahi-police-saw-nothing-1602220|title=Rajshahi police saw nothing!|date=9 July 2018 |work=The Daily Star |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"injured_quota_protester_2018_07_08_dhaka_tribune\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/07/08/injured-quota-reform-activist-tariqul-being-moved-to-dhaka-for-treatment|title=Injured quota protester Tariqul moved to Dhaka|date=8 July 2018|work=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Video and photos of the attack circulated on social media, prompting criticism over police and university administration inaction.<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_dailystar_net\" />\n\n==== Dhaka bus protests ====\n{{Main|2018 Bangladesh road safety protests}}\nOn 29 July 2018, two students were killed and a further twelve people were injured when a bus hit a bus stop in Dhaka. Protests began shortly afterwards, demanding better road safety. During the protests, BCL members were alleged to have been involved in numerous attacks on protestors throughout Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/dhaka/2018/08/04/live-students-block-streets-in-uttara|title=Minute by minute: Saturday\u2019s protest ends with violence in Jigatola |date=4 August 2018 |work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref> On 5 August 2018, a number of photojournalists were attacked, allegedly by members of the BCL wearing helmets. Law enforcement officers were present but did not make any attempt to stop the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/5-photojournalists-hurt-in-bcl-men-attack-science-lab-dhaka-student-protest-for-safe-roads-1616251|title=5 photojournalists hurt in \u2018BCL attack\u2019 |date=5 August 2018 |work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-08-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/160959|title=6 photojournalists injured in attacks by \u2018BCL\u2019 |date=5 August 2018|newspaper=The Independent|location=Bangladesh|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of student organizations in Bangladesh]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bangladesh Awami League}}\n\n[[Category:Student organisations in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Student wings of political parties in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Awami League]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi student movements]]\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1948]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh_Chhatra_League"}
{"title_page": "Bangalore Development Authority", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name = Bangalore Development Authority\n| type = Planning Authority\n| nativename = \n| nativename_a = \n| nativename_r = \n| logo = Bangalore_Development_Authority_logo.jpeg\n| logo_width = \n| logo_caption = Logo of the BDA\n| seal = \n| seal_width = \n| seal_caption = \n| picture = BDA Shopping Complex in Koramangala.JPG\n| picture_width = \n| picture_caption = A shopping complex built by the BDA on the Inner Ring Road, Koramangala\n| formed = {{Start date|df=yes|1976|01|06}}\n| preceding1 = \n| superseding = City Improvement Trust Board\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of Karnataka]]\n| headquarters = [[Bangalore]]\n| coordinates = <!--{{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}}-->\n| motto = \n| employees = 486<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bdabangalore.org/eng/Organization-Chart|title=Organization|website=Bengaluru Development Authority}}</ref>\n| budget = Rs. 5067.65 crore (2012)\n| minister1_name = \n| minister1_pfo = \n| minister2_name = \n| minister2_pfo = \n| minister3_name = [[B. S. Yediyurappa]]\n| chief1_name = Rakesh Singh\n| chief1_position = Commissioner\n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| agency_type = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency = \n| child1_agency = \n| child2_agency = \n| keydocument1 = \n| website = {{URL|bdabangalore.org}}\n| footnotes = \n| map = \n| map_width = \n| map_caption = \n}}\n\nThe '''Bangalore Development Authority''' ('''BDA''') of [[Bangalore]], [[India]], is a governmental organization (referred to within India as a [[State-owned enterprise|parastatal]] entity) and the principal planning authority for Bangalore. Its function, under the [[Karnataka]] Town and Country Planning Act of 1961 (KTCPA), is as a regulatory body required \"to prepare in the prescribed manner a Comprehensive Development Plan\" (CDP) for the Bangalore metropolitan region.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stallmeyer|first=John|title=Building Bangalore: Architecture and urban transformation in India\u2019s Silicon Valley|year=2010|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780203842195}}</ref> It also oversees planning and development of infrastructure, provision of development-related sites and services, the housing needs of underprivileged citizens in Bangalore and is currently the city's largest land developer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bangalore an IT city? Check with Bangalore Development Authority|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report_bangalore-an-it-city-check-with-bangalore-development-authority_1800196|newspaper=DNA|date=15 February 2013}}</ref> No other authority or person may undertake development within the Bangalore Metropolitan Region without the permission of the BDA.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lall|first=Somik V|title=Urban Land Markets: Improving Land Management for Successful Urbanization|year=2009|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781402088629|page=316}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nBDA was created on 6 January 1976 under the ''Bangalore Development Authority Act 1976''<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/07/19/stories/2006071907880400.htm | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Assembly re-adopts Bill on BDA Act | date=19 July 2006}}</ref> superseding the earlier civic authority known as the ''City Improvement Trust Board'' (CITB), but remaining nearly identical in function.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Building Bangalore: Architecture and urban transformation in India\u2019s Silicon Valley|last=Stallmeyer|first=John|publisher=Routledge|year=2010|isbn=1136903976|location=|pages=|chapter=Electronics City}}</ref> The BDA is a largely unelected local authority (2 out of 23 members are elected [[Bruhat Bengaluru Mahanagara Palike|BBMP]] corporators) with most of its members accountable to, and directly appointed by the state government. This creates issues with local representation, particularly since the passage of the [[List of amendments of the Constitution of India|Constitution (74th) Amendment Act, 1992]] mandating the devolution of planning powers to local, elected authorities.\n\nDespite being the principle planning authority, up to 90% of new residential layouts on the Bangalore periphery do not have formal approval from the BDA.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Urban Navigations: Politics, Space and the City in South Asia|last=Anjaria|first=Jonathan|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=1136197427|location=New Delhi|pages=168}}</ref> Over time, these layouts tend to be regularized by successive state governments, however they exhibit all of the issues associated with ad hoc residential development including irregular road layouts, boundary encroachments and lack of provision for essential services and infrastructure.\n\nCorruption has always been an issue within the BDA, with one particularly notorious scandal being the illegal sale of up to 200 sites in 1995 by corrupt BDA officials.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=|last=|first=|date=8 May 1995|work=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref> In the 1990s the BDA came under sustained criticism including the Public Affairs Center's 1993 report cards on BDA performance<ref>{{cite book|title=Benchmarking Urban Services: The Second Report Card from Bangalore|last=Paul|first=Samuel|publisher=Public Affairs Centre|year=2000}}</ref>; the  CUMB Report of 1997 which examined the role and function of the BDA and concluded that the organization had outlived its mandate, was failing as a development authority and should be disbanded;<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/185938374/Dr-Kasturirangan-Committee-Report-on-BBMP#fullscreen&from_embed|title=Report of the Expert Committee on Governance in the Bangalore Metropolitan Region and Bruhat Bangalore Mahanagara Palike|last=|first=|date=March 2008|publisher=Government of Karnataka|year=|isbn=|location=Bangalore|pages=}}</ref> and a 1999 report<ref>{{cite web|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTPCENG/1143333-1116505690049/20509275/making.pdf|title=Making Voice Work: The Report Card on Bangalore\u2019s Public Services|last=Paul|first=Samuel|date=November 1999|publisher=World Bank|doi=10.1596/1813-9450-1921}}</ref> by the [[World Bank]] which labelled it one of the most corrupt and inefficient institutions in the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/people/magazine/16-11/mf_mobgalore?currentPage=all|title=The Godfather of Bangalore|last=Carney|first=Scott|date=20 October 2008|newspaper=Wired}}</ref> The same report also reported on the findings of a citizen survey which found 65% of Bangaloreans dissatisfied with their experience dealing with the BDA, and just 1% satisfied\u2014the lowest of any civic agency in the city. It was also receiving the highest share of bribes (33%) in exchange for expediting service outcomes.\n\nThe BDA is credited with responding to these findings with some reforms in operational management and asset monitoring and accounting practices leading to a substantial increase in residential layout development and allocation.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Urban Land Markets: Improving Land Management for Successful Urbanization|last=Rajak|first=Robin|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2009|isbn=1402088620|editor-last=Lall|editor-first=Somik|location=|pages=320|chapter=Does Public Ownership and Management of Land Matter for Land Market Outcomes?}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the Kasturirangan Report reaffirmed that as both developer and land regulator, the BDA has neglected its regulatory role, but gained some additional credibility through the successful delivery of major infrastructure projects<ref name=\":0\" /> including the [[Outer Ring Road (Bangalore)|Outer Ring Road]], and various flyovers and underpasses throughout the city. The report recommended land regulation responsibilities be handed over to other municipal bodies such as the [[Bruhat Bengaluru Mahanagara Palike|BBMP]] with the BDA focusing on its function as a development body.\n\n==Achievements==\n\n* The superstructure of the [[Hebbal Flyover]] has won an award in the 9th Outstanding Bridge National Awards competition by the [[Indian Institute of Bridge, Engineers]] <ref>http://www.theretailtimes.co.in/April-e-paper.pdf</ref>\n* Restoration of [[Lake Agaram]]\n* Restoration of [[Benniganahalli Lake]]\n* Restoration of [[Lalbagh lake]]\n* Outer Ring Road\n\n==Criticism==\n* The encroachment and development upon water bodies and tanks essential for the city's drainage system.<ref>{{cite book|last=Srinivas|first=Smriti|title=Landscapes Of Urban Memory|year=2004|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=9788125022541|chapter=Models of the Garden City}}</ref><ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/475730/more-bda-layouts-lake-beds.html</ref>\n* Failure to provide basic amenities (power, water, sewerage, drainage) to residential layouts whilst embarking on still further projects.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Bangalore Development Authority needs major surgery\u2019|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report_bangalore-development-authority-needs-major-surgery_1711876|newspaper=DNA|date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=D'Souza|first=Odeal|title=Bangalore Development Authority acting like real estate agency: Karnataka high court|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report_bangalore-development-authority-acting-like-real-estate-agency-karnataka-high-court_1501644|newspaper=DNA|date=1 February 2011}}</ref>\n* Failure to provide for the rehabilitation of villagers displaced by new layout projects.<ref>{{cite news|last=D'Souza|first=Odeal|title=Bangalore Development Authority gets another sound rap from Karnataka high court|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report_bangalore-development-authority-gets-another-sound-rap-from-karnataka-high-court_1508581|newspaper=DNA|date=16 February 2011}}</ref>\n* Failure to deliver on planned projects and promised infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|last=Raghunandan|first=P|title=BDA's budget soars, progress dwindles|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/156679/bdas-budget-soars-progress-dwindles.html |newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=25 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Chaturvedi|first=Atul|title=Like BBMP, BDA too is a pauper|url=http://www.bangaloremirror.com/article/10/2013020820130208072148813342e5ead/Like-BBMP-BDA-too-is-a-pauper.html|newspaper=Bangalore Mirror|date=8 February 2013}}</ref>\n* Despite the 73rd and 74th amendments to the Indian Constitution devolving power to [[Panchayat]]s and local urban bodies, the BDA is not similarly responsive through an electoral process to local constituencies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stallmeyer|first=John|title=Building Bangalore: Architecture and urban transformation in India\u2019s Silicon Valley|year=2010|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780203842195}}</ref>\n* The influence of money and vested interests, the so-called \"land mafia\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Carney|first=Scott|title=The Godfather of Bangalore|url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/people/magazine/16-11/mf_mobgalore?currentPage=all|newspaper=Wired|date=20 October 2008}}</ref> in the violation of regulations and land use controls and the development of prime real estate locations.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stallmeyer|first=John|title=Building Bangalore: Architecture and urban transformation in India\u2019s Silicon Valley|year=2010|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780203842195}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BDA under heavy fire for its shady deals|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report_bda-under-heavy-fire-for-its-shady-deals_1720819|newspaper=DNA|date=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n* Service outcomes decreasing over time despite significant growth in revenues (accounting for population and inflation).<ref>{{cite book|last=Sridhar|first=Kala Seetharam|title=State of Urban Services in India's Cities: Spending and Financing|year=2010|publisher=Public Affairs Centre|isbn=9780198065388}}</ref>\n* HC calls BDA the mother of corruption. <ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/294643/hc-calls-bda-mother-corruption.html</ref>\n* Looks like it is not only BDA allotted sites that get into legal trouble, even auction sites which fetch the BDA crores of rupees that get entangled, in this case for 14 years. <ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/after-14-years-of-court-battle-infosys-employee-is-yet-to-get-his-bda-site/articleshow/60095645.cms</ref>\n* A series of denotifications hit the BDA arkavathy layout according to this source. This happened after BDA allotted the land to people who paid full amount for the site purchase from their hard earned savings and received lease cum sale agreements from BDA. So their money was with BDA but site GONE. <ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/another-285-acres-denotified-by-bda-in-arkavathy-layout/article4539155.ece</ref>\n* People who dare to build a house in a BDA developed layout, might have to stay with no power, water or drainage, not for years but decades as this one talks about facilities in Arkavathy layout and the facilities it offers.<ref>http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2018/mar/30/12-years-on-arkavathy-layout-to-get-power-supply-1794519.html</ref> <ref>https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/180416/cancel-sites-first-give-basic-amenities-arkavathy-allottees-association.html</ref>\n* Do you think BDA apartments are a safer bet, think again, a land owner allegedly cordoned off 300 BDA flat owners from an approach road<ref>https://www.deccanchronicle.com/140628/nation-current-affairs/article/bengaluru-development-authority-flats-no-safe-bet</ref>\n* BDA apartments and its amazing quality - read here <ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/565034/bda-flooded-complaints-unhappy-flat.html</ref> <ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Dreams-fall-flat-10-of-BDA-allottees-seek-refund/articleshow/44892153.cms</ref>\n* Yes, according to BDA, they refund people who withdraw their flat application but how easy is it to really get your money back is anyone's guess<ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/375252/flat-allottees-seek-refund-deposit.html</ref>\n* Hebbal flyover, designed and built by BDA is now bursting at the seams with unmanageable traffic according to this report <ref>https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/cover-story/hebbal-flyover-built-in-2003-seems-to-have-outlived-its-purpose/articleshow/68913144.cms</ref>. Does this showcase BDA's long term planning capabilities?\n\n==Layouts developed by BDA==\n*Jayanagar\n*Koramangala\n*J P Nagar\n*Anjanapura\n*Kumaraswamy Layout\n*Banashankari\n*Indiranagar\n*Domlur\n*Kasturi Nagar\n*Sadashivanagar\n*RMV Extension\n*HBR Layout\n*HRBR Layout\n*HSR Layout\n*BTM Layout\n*Vishweshwaraiah Layout\n*Arkavathy Layout\n*Nagarbhavi Layout\n*Banashankari 5th stage\n*Banashankari 6th stage\n*West of Chord Road Layout\n*Nadaprabhu Kempe Gowda Layout\n*Aecs layout A,B and C blocks ,kudlu gate\n\n==Names of some layouts with the original names of villages/ areas (after the hyphen (\u2018-\u2018))==\n*\n*EAST DIVISION\n*\n*H. A. L. II Stage (Part) \u2013 Dokkanahalli (Part)\n*Koramangala VI Block \u2013 Ijipura\n*Austin Town I, II & III Stages \u2013 Austin Town\n*Domlur Layout \u2013 Domlur\n*Koramangala IV Block \u2013 Koramangala\n*H. S. R. Layout - Agara, Yelikunte, Haralakunte & others\n*H. S. R. Layout III Sector \u2013 Haralakunte & Yelikunte\n*S. T. Bed \u2013 Shinivagilu\n*Sampigehalli I Stage - Sampige halli\n*Koramangala - Koramangala, Mastri Palya & Katli Palya\n*Layout between Appareddy Palya & Dokkanahally H. A. L II Stage \u2013 Dokkanahally\n*Domlur II Stage \u2013 Domlur\n*H. A. L. II Stage \u2013 Ko